&lt;h2 id=&#34;load-screen-savers&#34;&gt;Load Screen Savers&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;windows&#34;&gt;Windows&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Copy the *.scr file to &lt;code&gt;c:\Windows\System32&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Launch the Screensaver Windows Module (Start -&amp;gt; Run -&amp;gt; &lt;code&gt;control desk.cpl,,@screensaver&lt;/code&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Select the screensaver you copied&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Copy/Paste Run command:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;control desk.cpl,,@screensaver
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h3 id=&#34;linux&#34;&gt;Linux&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Loading scr files on Linux requires you to use WINE. You can launch this using wine.exe, but here is my article on setting it up as a systemd service: &lt;a href=&#34;https://christitus.com/lcars-screensaver/&#34;&gt;https://christitus.com/lcars-screensaver/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
